# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pairing-heap
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] In computer science, **amortized analysis** is a method for analyzing a given algorithm's complexity, or how much of a resource, especially time or memory, it takes to execute.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] The motivation for amortized analysis is that looking at the worst-case run time can be too pessimistic.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] Instead, amortized analysis averages the running times of operations in a sequence over that sequence.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] For a given operation of an algorithm, certain situations (e.g., input parametrizations or data structure contents) may imply a significant cost in resources, whereas other situations may not be as costly.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] The amortized analysis considers both the costly and less costly operations together over the whole sequence of operations.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] This may include accounting for different types of input, length of the input, and other factors that affect its performance.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis initially emerged from a method called aggregate analysis, which is now subsumed by amortized analysis.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] The technique was first formally introduced by Robert Tarjan in his 1985 paper *Amortized Computational Complexity*, which addressed the need for a more useful form of analysis than the common probabilistic methods used.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] Amortization was initially used for very specific types of algorithms, particularly those involving binary trees and union operations.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] However, it is now ubiquitous and comes into play when analyzing many other algorithms as well.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis requires knowledge of which series of operations are possible.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] This is most commonly the case with data structures, which have a state that persists between operations.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] The basic idea is that a worst-case operation can alter the state in such a way that the worst case cannot occur again for a long time, thus "amortizing" its cost.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] There are generally three methods for performing amortized analysis: the aggregate method, the accounting method, and the potential method.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] All of these give correct answers; the choice of which to use depends on which is most convenient for a particular situation.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] Consider a dynamic array that grows in size as more elements are added to it, such as `ArrayList` in Java or `std::vector` in C++.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] If we started out with a dynamic array of size 4, we could push 4 elements onto it, and each operation would take constant time.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] Yet pushing a fifth element onto that array would take longer as the array would have to create a new array of a scaled size, copy the old elements onto the new array, then add the new element.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] The next few push operations would similarly take constant time, then the subsequent addition would require another slow scaling of the array size.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] In general, for an arbitrary number n of pushes to an array of any initial size, the times for steps that scale the array add in a geometric series to $O(n)$ , while the constant times for each remaining push also add to $O(n)$ .
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] Therefore the average time per push operation is $O(n)/n=O(1)$ .
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] This reasoning can be formalized and generalized to more complicated data structures using amortized analysis.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] The enqueue operation just pushes an element onto the input array; this operation does not depend on the lengths of either input or output and therefore runs in constant time.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] However the dequeue operation is more complicated.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] If the output array already has some elements in it, then dequeue runs in constant time; otherwise, dequeue takes ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time to add all the elements onto the output array from the input array, where *n* is the current length of the input array.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] After copying *n* elements from input, we can perform *n* dequeue operations, each taking constant time, before the output array is empty again.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] Thus, we can perform a sequence of *n* dequeue operations in only ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, which implies that the amortized time of each dequeue operation is ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] Alternatively, we can charge the cost of copying any item from the input array to the output array to the earlier enqueue operation for that item.
[src:pairing-heap/amortized-analysis] This charging scheme doubles the amortized time for enqueue but reduces the amortized time for dequeue to ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] In computer science, a **Fibonacci heap** is a data structure for priority queue operations, consisting of a collection of heap-ordered trees.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] It has a better amortized running time than many other priority queue data structures including the binary heap and binomial heap.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Tarjan developed Fibonacci heaps in 1984 and published them in a scientific journal in 1987.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Fibonacci heaps are named after the Fibonacci numbers, which are used in their running time analysis.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amortized times of all operations on Fibonacci heaps is constant, except *delete-min*.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Deleting an element (most often used in the special case of deleting the minimum element) works in $O(\log n)$ amortized time, where n is the size of the heap.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This means that starting from an empty data structure, any sequence of *a* insert and *decrease-key* operations and *b* *delete-min* operations would take $O(a+b\log n)$ worst case time, where n is the maximum heap size.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] In a binary or binomial heap, such a sequence of operations would take $O((a+b)\log n)$ time.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] A Fibonacci heap is thus better than a binary or binomial heap when b is smaller than a by a non-constant factor.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] It is also possible to merge two Fibonacci heaps in constant amortized time, improving on the logarithmic merge time of a binomial heap, and improving on binary heaps which cannot handle merges efficiently.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Using Fibonacci heaps improves the asymptotic running time of algorithms which utilize priority queues.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] For example, Dijkstra's algorithm and Prim's algorithm can be made to run in $O(|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ time.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] A Fibonacci heap is a collection of trees satisfying the minimum-heap property, that is, the key of a child is always greater than or equal to the key of the parent.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This implies that the minimum key is always at the root of one of the trees.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Compared with binomial heaps, the structure of a Fibonacci heap is more flexible.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The trees do not have a prescribed shape and in the extreme case the heap can have every element in a separate tree.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This flexibility allows some operations to be executed in a lazy manner, postponing the work for later operations.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] For example, merging heaps is done simply by concatenating the two lists of trees, and operation *decrease key* sometimes cuts a node from its parent and forms a new tree.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] However, at some point order needs to be introduced to the heap to achieve the desired running time.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] In particular, degrees of nodes (here degree means the number of direct children) are kept quite low: every node has degree at most $\log n$ and the size of a subtree rooted in a node of degree k is at least $F_{k+2}$ , where $F_{i}$ is the i th Fibonacci number.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This is achieved by the rule: at most one child can be cut off each non-root node.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] When a second child is cut, the node itself needs to be cut from its parent and becomes the root of a new tree (see Proof of degree bounds, below).
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The number of trees is decreased in the operation *delete-min*, where trees are linked together.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] As a result of a relaxed structure, some operations can take a long time while others are done very quickly.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] For the amortized running time analysis, we use the potential method, in that we pretend that very fast operations take a little bit longer than they actually do.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This additional time is then later combined and subtracted from the actual running time of slow operations.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amount of time saved for later use is measured at any given moment by a potential function.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The potential $\phi$ of a Fibonacci heap is given by $\phi =t+2m,$ where t is the number of trees in the Fibonacci heap, and m is the number of marked nodes.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] A node is marked if at least one of its children was cut, since this node was made a child of another node (all roots are unmarked).
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amortized time for an operation is given by the sum of the actual time and c times the difference in potential, where *c* is a constant (chosen to match the constant factors in the big O notation for the actual time).
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Thus, the root of each tree in a heap has one unit of time stored.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This unit of time can be used later to link this tree with another tree at amortized time 0.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Also, each marked node has two units of time stored.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] One can be used to cut the node from its parent.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] If this happens, the node becomes a root and the second unit of time will remain stored in it as in any other root.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] To allow fast deletion and concatenation, the roots of all trees are linked using a circular doubly linked list.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The children of each node are also linked using such a list.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] For each node, we maintain its number of children and whether the node is marked.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] We maintain a pointer to the root containing the minimum key, allowing $O(1)$ access to the minimum.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This pointer must be updated during the other operations, which adds only a constant time overhead.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The merge operation simply concatenates the root lists of two heaps together and sets the minimum to be the smaller of the two heaps.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This can be done in constant time, and the potential does not change, leading again to constant amortized time.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The insertion operation can be considered a special case of the merge operation, with a single node.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The node is simply appended to the root list, increasing the potential by one.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amortized cost is thus still constant.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The delete-min operation does most of the work in restoring the structure of the heap.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] We therefore decrease the number of roots by successively linking together roots of the same degree.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] When two roots have the same degree, we make the one with the larger key a child of the other, so that the minimum heap property is conserved.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The degree of the smaller root increases by one.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This is repeated until every root has a different degree.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] To find trees of the same degree efficiently, we use an array of length $O(\log n)$ in which we keep a pointer to one root of each degree.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] When a second root is found of the same degree, the two are linked and the array is updated.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The actual running time is $O(\log n+m)$ , where m is the number of roots at the beginning of the second phase.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] In the end, we will have at most $O(\log n)$ roots (because each has a different degree).
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Therefore, the difference in the potential from before to after this phase is $O(\log n)-m$ .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Thus, the amortized running time is $O(\log n+m)+c(O(\log n)-m)$ .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] By choosing a sufficiently large c such that the terms in m cancel out, this simplifies to $O(\log n)$ .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Search the final list of roots to find the minimum, and update the minimum pointer accordingly.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This takes $O(\log n)$ time, because the number of roots has been reduced.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Overall, the amortized time of this operation is $O(\log n)$ , provided that $d=O(\log n)$ .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The proof of this is given in the following section.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] If decreasing the key of a node x causes it to become smaller than its parent, then it is cut from its parent, becoming a new unmarked root.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] If it is also less than the minimum key, then the minimum pointer is updated.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] We then initiate a series of *cascading cuts*, starting with the parent of x .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] As long as the current node is marked, it is cut from its parent and made an unmarked root.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This process stops when we reach an unmarked node y .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] In this process we introduce some number, say k , of new trees.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Except possibly x , each of these new trees loses its original mark.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The terminating node y may become marked.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Therefore, the change in the number of marked nodes is between of $-k$ and $-k+2$ .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The resulting change in potential is $k+2(-k+2)=-k+4$ .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The actual time required to perform the cutting was $O(k)$ .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Hence, the amortized time is $O(k)+c(-k+4)$ , which is constant, provided c is sufficiently large.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The amortized performance of a Fibonacci heap depends on the degree (number of children) of any tree root being $O(\log n)$ , where n is the size of the heap.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Here we show that the size of the (sub)tree rooted at any node x of degree d in the heap must have size at least $F_{d+2}$ , where $F_{i}$ is the i th Fibonacci number.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The degree bound follows from this and the fact (easily proved by induction) that $F_{d+2}\geq \varphi ^{d}$ for all integers $d\geq 0$ , where $\varphi =(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2\approx 1.618$ is the golden ratio.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] We then have $n\geq F_{d+2}\geq \varphi ^{d}$ , and taking the log to base $\varphi$ of both sides gives $d\leq \log _{\varphi }n$ as required.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Let x be an arbitrary node in a Fibonacci heap, not necessarily a root.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Define $\mathrm {size} (x)$ to be the size of the tree rooted at x (the number of descendants of x , including x itself).
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] We prove by induction on the height of x (the length of the longest path from x to a descendant leaf) that $\mathrm {size} (x)\geq F_{d+2}$ , where d is the degree of x .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] We claim that $c_{i}\geq i-2$ for each i .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Just before $y_{i}$ was made a child of x , $y_{1}\dots y_{i-1}$ were already children of x , and so x must have had degree at least $i-1$ at that time.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Since trees are combined only when the degrees of their roots are equal, it must have been the case that $y_{i}$ also had degree at least $i-1$ at the time when it became a child of x .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] From that time to the present, $y_{i}$ could have only lost at most one child (as guaranteed by the marking process), and so its current degree $c_{i}$ is at least $i-2$ .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This gives the desired lower bound on $\mathrm {size} (x)$ .
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] They are not as efficient in practice when compared with theoretically less efficient forms of heaps.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] In their simplest version, they require manipulation of four pointers per node, whereas only two or three pointers per node are needed in other structures, such as the binomial heap, or pairing heap.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] This results in large memory consumption per node and high constant factors on all operations.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Although the total running time of a sequence of operations starting with an empty structure is bounded by the bounds given above, some (very few) operations in the sequence can take very long to complete (in particular, delete-min has linear running time in the worst case).
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] For this reason, Fibonacci heaps and other amortized data structures may not be appropriate for real-time systems.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] It is possible to create a data structure which has the same worst-case performance as the Fibonacci heap has amortized performance.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] One such structure, the Brodal queue, is, in the words of the creator, "quite complicated" and "[not] applicable in practice." Invented in 2012, the strict Fibonacci heap is a simpler (compared to Brodal's) structure with the same worst-case bounds.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Despite being simpler, experiments show that in practice the strict Fibonacci heap performs slower than more complicated Brodal queue and also slower than basic Fibonacci heap.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The run-relaxed heaps of Driscoll et al. give good worst-case performance for all Fibonacci heap operations except merge.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Recent experimental results suggest that the Fibonacci heap is more efficient in practice than most of its later derivatives, including quake heaps, violation heaps, strict Fibonacci heaps, and rank pairing heaps, but less efficient than pairing heaps or array-based heaps.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] For persistent heaps (not supporting *decrease-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-min* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-min* and *meld*.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-min* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:pairing-heap/fibonacci-heap] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *decrease-key* is not supported.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] In computer science, a **heap** is a tree-based data structure that satisfies the **heap property**: In a *max heap*, for any given node C, if P is the parent node of C, then the *key* (the *value*) of P is greater than or equal to the key of C.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] In a *min heap*, the key of P is less than or equal to the key of C.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] The node at the "top" of the heap (with no parents) is called the *root* node.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap is one maximally efficient implementation of an abstract data type called a priority queue, and in fact, priority queues are often referred to as "heaps", regardless of how they may be implemented.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] In a heap, the highest (or lowest) priority element is always stored at the root.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] However, a heap is not a sorted structure; it can be regarded as being partially ordered.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] A heap is a useful data structure when it is necessary to repeatedly remove the object with the highest (or lowest) priority, or when insertions need to be interspersed with removals of the root node.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] A common implementation of a heap is the binary heap, in which the tree is a complete binary tree (see figure).
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure, specifically the binary heap, was introduced by J.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] Williams in 1964, as a data structure for the heapsort sorting algorithm.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are also crucial in several efficient graph algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] When a heap is a complete binary tree, it has the smallest possible height—a heap with *N* nodes and *a* branches for each node always has log*a* *N* height.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] Note that, as shown in the graphic, there is no implied ordering between siblings or cousins and no implied sequence for an in-order traversal (as there would be in, e.g., a binary search tree).
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap relation mentioned above applies only between nodes and their parents, grandparents.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] The maximum number of children each node can have depends on the type of heap.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are typically constructed in-place in the same array where the elements are stored, with their structure being implicit in the access pattern of the operations.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps differ in this way from other data structures with similar or in some cases better theoretic bounds such as radix trees in that they require no additional memory beyond that used for storing the keys.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] For a binary heap, in the array, the first index contains the root element.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] The next two indices of the array contain the root's children.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] The next four indices contain the four children of the root's two child nodes, and so on.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] Therefore, given a node at index i, its children are at indices ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $2i+2$ ⁠, and its parent is at index ⌊(*i*−1)/2⌋ in an array starting from index ⁠ 0 ⁠, or at ⁠ $2i$ ⁠, ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠, and ⌊*i*/2⌋, respectively, in an array starting from ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] This simple indexing scheme makes it efficient to walk "up" or "down" the tree.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] Balancing a heap is done by sift-up or sift-down operations (swapping elements which are out of order).
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] As we can build a heap from an array without requiring extra memory (for the nodes, for example), heapsort can be used to sort an array in-place.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] After an element is inserted into or deleted from a heap, the heap property may be violated, and the heap must be re-balanced by swapping elements within the array.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] This is faster than a sequence of consecutive insertions into an originally empty heap, which is log-linear.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] *make-heap* is the operation of building a heap from a sequence of *n* unsorted elements.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] It can be done in *Θ*(*n*) time whenever *meld* runs in *O*(log *n*) time (where both complexities can be amortized).
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] Another algorithm achieves *Θ*(*n*) for binary heaps.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] For persistent heaps (not supporting *increase-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-max* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-max* and *meld*.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-max* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *increase-key* is not supported.
[src:pairing-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure has many applications.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] A **pairing heap** is a type of heap data structure with relatively simple implementation and excellent practical amortized performance, introduced by Michael Fredman, Robert Sedgewick, Daniel Sleator, and Robert Tarjan in 1986.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] Pairing heaps are heap-ordered multiway tree structures, and can be considered simplified Fibonacci heaps.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] The analysis of pairing heaps' time complexity was initially inspired by that of splay trees.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] The amortized time per *delete-min* is *O*(log *n*), and the operations *find-min*, *meld*, and *insert* run in *O*(1) time.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] When a *decrease-key* operation is added as well, determining the precise asymptotic running time of pairing heaps has turned out to be difficult.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] Initially, the time complexity of this operation was conjectured on empirical grounds to be *O*(1), but Fredman proved that the amortized time per *decrease-key* is at least $\Omega (\log \log n)$ for some sequences of operations.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] Using a different amortization argument, Pettie then proved that *insert*, *meld*, and *decrease-key* all run in $O(2^{2{\sqrt {\log \log n}}})$ amortized time, which is $o(\log n)$ .
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] Elmasry later introduced elaborations of pairing heaps (lazy, consolidate) for which *decrease-key* runs in $O(\log \log n)$ amortized time and other operations have optimal amortized bounds, but no tight $\Theta (\log \log n)$ bound is known for the original data structure.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] Although the asymptotic performance of pairing heaps is worse than other priority queue algorithms such as Fibonacci heaps, which perform *decrease-key* in $O(1)$ amortized time, the performance in practice is excellent.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] Jones and Larkin, Sen, and Tarjan conducted experiments on pairing heaps and other heap data structures.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] A pairing heap is either an empty heap, or a pairing tree consisting of a root element and a possibly empty list of pairing trees.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] The heap ordering property requires that parent of any node is no greater than the node itself.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] The following description assumes a purely functional heap that does not support the *decrease-key* operation.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] It can also be viewed as a variant of a Left-child right-sibling binary tree with an additional pointer to a node's parent (which represents its previous sibling or actual parent for the leftmost sibling).
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] Alternatively, the previous-pointer can be omitted by letting the last child point back to the parent, if a single Boolean flag is added to indicate "end of list".
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] This achieves a more compact structure at the expense of a constant overhead factor per operation.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] The only non-trivial fundamental operation is the deletion of the minimum element from the heap.
[src:pairing-heap/pairing-heap] This requires performing repeated melds of its children until only one tree remains.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In computer science, a **priority queue** is an abstract data type similar to a regular queue where each element has an associated priority determining its order of service.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Priority queue serves highest priority items first.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Priority values have to be instances of an ordered data type, and higher priority can be given either to the lesser or to the greater values with respect to the given order relation.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For example, in the Java standard library, the PriorityQueue class considers the lowest element with respect to their order as having the highest priority.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] While priority queues are often implemented using heaps, they are conceptually distinct.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue can be implemented with a heap or with other methods; just as a list can be implemented with a linked list or with an array.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Stacks and queues can be implemented as particular kinds of priority queues, with the priority determined by the order in which the elements are inserted.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In a stack, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically increasing; thus, the last element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In a queue, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically decreasing; thus, the first element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In some implementations, if two elements have the same priority, they are served in the same order in which they were enqueued.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In other implementations, the order of elements with the same priority is undefined.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] One can create a simple, but inefficient priority queue in a number of ways.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] These naive implementations can demonstrate the expected behaviour of a priority queue in a simpler manner.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] To improve performance, priority queues are typically based on a heap, giving $O(\log n)$ performance for inserts and removals, and $O(n)$ to build the heap initially from a set of n elements.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Variants of the basic heap data structure such as pairing heaps or Fibonacci heaps can provide better bounds for some operations.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] From a space-complexity standpoint, using self-balancing binary search tree with linked list takes more storage, since it requires storing extra references to other nodes.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] From a computational-complexity standpoint, priority queues are congruent to sorting algorithms.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The section on the equivalence of priority queues and sorting algorithms, below, describes how efficient sorting algorithms can create efficient priority queues.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] There are several specialized heap data structures that either supply additional operations or outperform heap-based implementations for specific types of keys, specifically integer keys.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For applications that do many "peek" operations for every "`extract-min`" operation, the time complexity for peek actions can be reduced to $O(1)$ in all tree and heap implementations by caching the highest priority element after every insertion and removal.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For insertion, this adds at most a constant cost, since the newly inserted element is compared only to the previously cached minimum element.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For deletion, this at most adds an additional "peek" cost, which is typically cheaper than the deletion cost, so overall time complexity is not significantly impacted.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Monotone priority queues are specialized queues that are optimized for the case where no item is ever inserted that has a lower priority (in the case of min-heap) than any item previously extracted.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This restriction is met by several practical applications of priority queues.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The semantics of priority queues naturally suggest a sorting method: insert all the elements to be sorted into a priority queue, and sequentially remove them; they will come out in sorted order.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This is actually the procedure used by several sorting algorithms, once the layer of abstraction provided by the priority queue is removed.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] A sorting algorithm can also be used to implement a priority queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For example, if one has an $O(n\log n)$ sort algorithm, one can create a priority queue with $O(1)$ pulling and $O(\log n)$ insertion.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is often considered to be a "container data structure".
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The Standard Template Library (STL), and the C++ 1998 standard, specifies std::priority_queue as one of the STL container adaptor class templates.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] However, it does not specify how two elements with same priority should be served, and indeed, common implementations will not return them according to their order in the queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Unlike actual STL containers, it does not allow iteration of its elements (it strictly adheres to its abstract data type definition).
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] STL also has utility functions for manipulating another random-access container as a binary max-heap.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The Boost libraries also have an implementation in the library heap.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Python's heapq module implements a binary min-heap on top of a list.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Java's library contains a `PriorityQueue` (`java.util.PriorityQueue`) class, which implements a min-priority-queue as a binary heap.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] .NET's library contains a System.Collections.Generic.PriorityQueue class, which implements an array-backed, quaternary min-heap.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Scala's library contains a scala.collection.mutable.PriorityQueue class, which implements a max-priority-queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Go's library contains a container/heap module, which implements a min-heap on top of any compatible data structure.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Rust's standard library contains a std::collections::BinaryHeap struct, which implements a priority queue with a binary heap.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The Standard PHP Library extension contains the class SplPriorityQueue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Apple's Core Foundation framework contains a CFBinaryHeap structure, which implements a min-heap.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Priority queuing can be used to manage limited resources such as bandwidth on a transmission line from a network router.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In the event of outgoing traffic queuing due to insufficient bandwidth, all other queues can be halted to send the traffic from the highest priority queue upon arrival.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that the prioritized traffic (such as real-time traffic, e.g. an RTP stream of a VoIP connection) is forwarded with the least delay and the least likelihood of being rejected due to a queue reaching its maximum capacity.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] All other traffic can be handled when the highest priority queue is empty.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Another approach used is to send disproportionately more traffic from higher priority queues.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Many modern protocols for local area networks also include the concept of priority queues at the media access control (MAC) sub-layer to ensure that high-priority applications (such as VoIP or IPTV) experience lower latency than other applications which can be served with best-effort service.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Examples include IEEE 802.11e (an amendment to IEEE 802.11 which provides quality of service) and ITU-T G.hn (a standard for high-speed local area network using existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables).
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Usually a limitation (policer) is set to limit the bandwidth that traffic from the highest priority queue can take, in order to prevent high priority packets from choking off all other traffic.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This limit is usually never reached due to high level control instances such as the Cisco Callmanager, which can be programmed to inhibit calls which would exceed the programmed bandwidth limit.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Another use of a priority queue is to manage the events in a discrete event simulation.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The events are added to the queue with their simulation time used as the priority.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The execution of the simulation proceeds by repeatedly pulling the top of the queue and executing the event thereon.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] When the graph is stored in the form of adjacency list or matrix, priority queue can be used to extract minimum efficiently when implementing Dijkstra's algorithm, although one also needs the ability to alter the priority of a particular vertex in the priority queue efficiently.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] If instead, a graph is stored as node objects, and priority-node pairs are inserted into a heap, altering the priority of a particular vertex is not necessary if one tracks visited nodes.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Once a node is visited, if it comes up in the heap again (having had a lower priority number associated with it earlier), it is popped-off and ignored.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Huffman coding requires one to repeatedly obtain the two lowest-frequency trees.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is one method of doing this.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Best-first search algorithms, like the A* search algorithm, find the shortest path between two vertices or nodes of a weighted graph, trying out the most promising routes first.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue (also known as the *fringe*) is used to keep track of unexplored routes; the one for which the estimate (a lower bound in the case of A*) of the total path length is smallest is given highest priority.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] If memory limitations make best-first search impractical, variants like the SMA* algorithm can be used instead, with a double-ended priority queue to allow removal of low-priority items.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The Real-time Optimally Adapting Meshes (ROAM) algorithm computes a dynamically changing triangulation of a terrain.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] It works by splitting triangles where more detail is needed and merging them where less detail is needed.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm assigns each triangle in the terrain a priority, usually related to the error decrease if that triangle would be split.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm uses two priority queues, one for triangles that can be split and another for triangles that can be merged.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In each step the triangle from the split queue with the highest priority is split, or the triangle from the merge queue with the lowest priority is merged with its neighbours.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Using min heap priority queue in Prim's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a connected and undirected graph, one can achieve a good running time.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This min heap priority queue uses the min heap data structure which supports operations such as `insert`, `minimum`, `extract-min`, `decrease-key`.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In this implementation, the weight of the edges is used to decide the priority of the vertices.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Lower the weight, higher the priority and higher the weight, lower the priority.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Parallelization can be used to speed up priority queues, but requires some changes to the priority queue interface.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The reason for such changes is that a sequential update usually only has ${\textstyle O(1)}$ or ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost, and there is no practical gain to parallelize such an operation.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] One possible change is to allow the concurrent access of multiple processors to the same priority queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The second possible change is to allow batch operations that work on ${\textstyle k}$ elements, instead of just one element.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For example, `extractMin` will remove the first ${\textstyle k}$ elements with the highest priority.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] If the priority queue allows concurrent access, multiple processes can perform operations concurrently on that priority queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] First of all, the definition of the semantics of the individual operations is no longer obvious.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For example, if two processes want to extract the element with the highest priority, should they get the same element or different ones?
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This restricts parallelism on the level of the program using the priority queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In addition, because multiple processes have access to the same element, this leads to contention.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The concurrent access to a priority queue can be implemented on a Concurrent Read, Concurrent Write (CRCW) PRAM model.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In the following the priority queue is implemented as a skip list.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In addition, an atomic synchronization primitive, CAS, is used to make the skip list lock-free.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The nodes of the skip list consists of a unique key, a priority, an array of pointers, for each level, to the next nodes and a `delete` mark.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The `delete` mark marks if the node is about to be deleted by a process.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that other processes can react to the deletion appropriately.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] If the concurrent access to a priority queue is allowed, conflicts may arise between two processes.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For example, a conflict arises if one process is trying to insert a new node, but at the same time another process is about to delete the predecessor of that node.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] There is a risk that the new node is added to the skip list, yet it is not longer reachable.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In this setting, operations on a priority queue is generalized to a batch of ${\textstyle k}$ elements.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_extract-min` deletes the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the priority queue and returns those.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In a shared-memory setting, the parallel priority queue can be easily implemented using parallel binary search trees and join-based tree algorithms.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] In particular, `k_extract-min` corresponds to a *split* on the binary search tree that has ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost and yields a tree that contains the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] `k_insert` can be applied by a *union* of the original priority queue and the batch of insertions.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] If the batch is already sorted by the key, `k_insert` has ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}}))}$ cost.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Otherwise, we need to first sort the batch, so the cost will be ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}})+k\log k)=O(k\log n)}$ .
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Other operations for priority queue can be applied similarly.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_decrease-key` can be done by first applying `difference` and then `union`, which first deletes the elements and then inserts them back with the updated keys.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] All these operations are highly parallel, and the theoretical and practical efficiency can be found in related research papers.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The rest of this section discusses a queue-based algorithm on distributed memory.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] We assume each processor has its own local memory and a local (sequential) priority queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The elements of the global (parallel) priority queue are distributed across all processors.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] A `k_insert` operation assigns the elements uniformly random to the processors which insert the elements into their local queues.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Note that single elements can still be inserted into the queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Using this strategy the global smallest elements are in the union of the local smallest elements of every processor with high probability.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Thus each processor holds a representative part of the global priority queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This property is used when `k_extract-min` is executed, as the smallest ${\textstyle m}$ elements of each local queue are removed and collected in a result set.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The elements in the result set are still associated with their original processor.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The number of elements ${\textstyle m}$ that is removed from each local queue depends on ${\textstyle k}$ and the number of processors ${\textstyle p}$ .
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] By parallel selection the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the result set are determined.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] With high probability these are the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] If not, ${\textstyle m}$ elements are again removed from each local queue and put into the result set.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This is done until the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements are in the result set.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Now these ${\textstyle k}$ elements can be returned.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] All other elements of the result set are inserted back into their local queues.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The running time of `k_extract-min` is expected ${\textstyle O({\frac {k}{p}}\log(n))}$ , where ${\textstyle k=\Omega (p\cdot \log(p))}$ and ${\textstyle n}$ is the size of the priority queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The priority queue can be further improved by not moving the remaining elements of the result set directly back into the local queues after a `k_extract-min` operation.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] This saves moving elements back and forth all the time between the result set and the local queues.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] By removing several elements at once a considerable speedup can be reached.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] But not all algorithms can use this kind of priority queue.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] Dijkstra's algorithm for example can not work on several nodes at once.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm takes the node with the smallest distance from the priority queue and calculates new distances for all its neighbor nodes.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] If you would take out ${\textstyle k}$ nodes, working at one node could change the distance of another one of the ${\textstyle k}$ nodes.
[src:pairing-heap/priority-queue] So using k-element operations destroys the label setting property of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] In computer science, a **soft heap** is a variant on the simple heap data structure that has constant amortized time complexity for 5 types of operations.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] This is achieved by carefully "corrupting" (increasing) the keys of at most a constant number of values in the heap.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Other heaps such as Fibonacci heaps achieve most of these bounds without any corruption, but cannot provide a constant-time bound on the critical *delete* operation.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] The amount of corruption can be controlled by the choice of a parameter $\varepsilon$ , but the lower this is set, the more time insertions require: expressed using Big-O notation, the amortized time will be $O(\log 1/\varepsilon )$ for an error rate of $\varepsilon$ .
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Some versions of soft heaps allow the *create*, *insert*, and *meld* operations to take constant time in the worst case, producing amortized rather than worst-case performance only for findmin and delete.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] As with comparison sort, these algorithms access the keys only by comparisons; if arithmetic operations on integer keys are allowed, the time dependence on $\varepsilon$ can be reduced to $O(\log \log 1/\varepsilon )$ or (with randomization) ${\textstyle O({\sqrt {\log \log 1/\varepsilon }})}$ .
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] More precisely, the error guarantee offered by the soft heap is the following: each soft heap is initialized with a parameter $\varepsilon$ , chosen between 0 and 1/2.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Then at any point in time it will contain at most $\varepsilon \cdot n$ corrupted keys, where n is the number of elements inserted so far.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Note that this does not guarantee that only a fixed percentage of the keys *currently* in the heap are corrupted: in an unlucky sequence of insertions and deletions, it can happen that all elements in the heap will have corrupted keys.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Similarly, there is no guarantee that in a sequence of elements extracted from the heap with *findmin* and *delete*, only a fixed percentage will have corrupted keys: in an unlucky scenario only corrupted elements are extracted from the heap.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] When a key is corrupted, the value stored for it in the soft key is higher than its initially-given value; corruption can never decrease the value of any key.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] The *findmin* operation finds the minimum value among the currently stored keys, including the corrupted ones.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] The soft heap was designed by Bernard Chazelle in 2000.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] The term "corruption" in the structure is the result of what Chazelle called "carpooling" in a soft heap.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Each node in the soft heap contains a linked list of keys and one common key.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] The common key is an upper bound on the values of the keys in the linked list.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Once a key is added to the linked list, it is considered corrupted because its value is never again relevant in any of the soft heap operations: only the common keys are compared.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] This is what makes soft heaps "soft"; one cannot be sure whether any particular value put into it will be corrupted.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] The purpose of these corruptions is effectively to lower the information entropy of the data, enabling the data structure to break through information-theoretic barriers regarding heaps.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Despite their limitations and unpredictable nature, soft heaps are useful in the design of deterministic algorithms.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] For instance, they have been used to achieve the best complexity to date for finding a minimum spanning tree.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Other problems whose efficient solution has been simplified using soft heaps include finding the k th smallest element in several classes of structured sets of values, including heap-ordered trees, sorted matrices, and sumsets.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] After the comparison step of the algorithm, the first of the two subsets contains all of the deleted keys, so it includes at least $n/3$ elements.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Among the $2n/3$ elements that were not deleted, at most $n/3$ are corrupted, so at least $n/3$ are uncorrupted.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] These uncorrupted and undeleted elements must all belong to the second subset, because they are greater than or equal to the soft heap's (possibly corrupted) value of L , which is in turn greater than the true value of L .
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Thus, both subsets have between 33% and 66% of the elements.
[src:pairing-heap/soft-heap] Because each level of recursion reduces the problem size by a constant factor, the total time of the algorithm can be bounded by a geometric series, showing that it is $O(n)$ .
